# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Critical Breaking Change

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised. Your `Stop()` method will crash and your cleanup logic will never execute.

## Migrated Code Using `CancellationToken`

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token); // pass token to unblock
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException handling
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful exit with a timeout
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Abort() in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has no `Thread.Abort()` replacement. You *must* make your code cooperatively cancellable. |
| **Blocking calls** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take()`), pass `CancellationToken` so it throws `OperationCanceledException`. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` gone** | Calling it throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Remove entirely. |
| **`volatile bool` insufficient** | A `volatile` flag can't interrupt a blocking call. `CancellationToken` can. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` for timing** | Replace with `await Task.Delay(timeout, token)` — it's cancellable. |
| **Fire-and-forget risks** | Use `Task.Run` + store the `Task` so exceptions are observed and you can await shutdown. |

## If You Can't Make Blocking Code Async

For legacy synchronous APIs that don't accept `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Poll with short timeout instead of indefinite block
        if (TryGetNextItem(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(500), out var item))
        {
            ProcessItem(item);
        }
    }
    RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    FlushBuffers();
}
```

## Migration Checklist

1. Replace `volatile bool` → `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken`
2. Remove all `Thread.Abort()` / `ResetAbort()` calls
3. Replace `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`
4. Pass `CancellationToken` into all blocking/async methods
5. Replace `Thread` + `IsBackground` → `Task.Run` (tasks are already background)
6. Replace synchronous `Stop()` → `async StopAsync()` with timeout
7. Implement `IDisposable` for deterministic cleanup
